'''Bartholomaeus of Bruges''' ('''Barthélemy de Bruges''') (died 1356) was a Flemish physician and natural philosopher.
==Life== He graduated M.A. at the [[University of Paris]] in 1307, and became a master of medicine. He came under the influence of [[Radulphus Brito]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Benoît Patar|title=Dictionnaire des Philosophes Médiévaux|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AX-Mi1XklNoC&pg=PA96|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=2006|publisher=Les Editions Fides|isbn=978-2-7621-2741-6|pages=95–6|language=fr}}</ref>
Bartholomaeus served as physician to [[Guy I, Count of Blois]] until the count died.<ref name="MaierùBagliani">{{cite book|author1=Alfonso Maierù|author2=Alfonso Maierù - Agostino Paravicini Bagliani|title=Studi sul XIV secolo in memoria di Anneliese Maier|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f26vF4czPg0C&pg=PA418|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=Ed. di Storia e Letteratura|page=418|id=GGKEY:L405NCPNGP7}}</ref> He was a reforming medical teacher, replacing the older curriculum based on the ''[[Articella]]'' by a new [[Galenism]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Luis Garcia-Ballester|author2=Roger French|author3=Jon Arrizabalaga|author4=Andrew Cunningham|title=Practical Medicine from Salerno to the Black Death|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nYQeixG4zrQC&pg=PA50|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=16 December 1993|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-43101-9|page=50}}</ref>
==Works== Bartholomaeus wrote commentaries on [[Aristotle]].<ref name="GlickLivesey2005">{{cite book|author1=Thomas F. Glick|author2=Steven J. Livesey|author3=Faith Wallis|title=Medieval Science, Technology, and Medicine: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SaJlbWK_-FcC&pg=PA76|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=29 September 2005|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-96930-7|page=76}}</ref><ref>[http://www.colorado.edu/philosophy/provisionalia/#bobr colorado.edu/philosophy/provisionalia, ''Bartholomew of Bruges''.]</ref> His work on the ''[[Poetics (Aristotle)|Poetics]]'' is noted for its sympathy with [[mimesis]] as a poetical function, and so an opening towards classical drama<ref>{{cite book|author=Donnalee Dox|title=The Idea of the Theater in Latin Christian Thought: Augustine to the Fourteenth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rPxyCaOBHhcC&pg=PA116|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=5 August 2004|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0-472-11423-8|pages=116–7}}</ref> (the original work of Aristotle not being available at the time in Western Europe, the basis was a Latin translation by [[Hermannus Alemannus]] from [[Averroes]], the ''Commentaria Media'').<ref>{{cite book|author1=Perrine Galand-Hallyn|author2=Fernand Hallyn|author3=Terence Cave|title=Poétiques de la Renaissance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pSCtRwTJcPcC&pg=PA49|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=2001|publisher=Librairie Droz|isbn=978-2-600-00474-9|pages=49–|language=fr}}</ref> He engaged in controversy with [[John of Jandun]] on the ''[[sensus agens]]'', an active perceptive faculty of the soul.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Simo Knuuttila|author2=Pekka Kärkkäinen|title=Theories of Perception in Medieval and Early Modern Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8dM6T86QreYC&pg=PA215|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=20 March 2008|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-4020-6124-0|page=215}}</ref> The reply of John of Jandun has been dated to 1310.<ref>{{cite book|author=A. Pattin|title=Pour l'histoire du sens agent: La controverse entre Barthélemy de Bruges et Jean de Jandun. Ses antécédents et son évolution. Etudes de textes inédits|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IdRE4vgXrVQC&pg=PA32|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=1 January 1988|publisher=Leuven University Press|isbn=978-90-6186-263-5|page=32}}</ref>
At the [[University of Montpellier]] he wrote also on the ''[[Ars Medicine]]''.<ref name="O'Boyle1998">{{cite book|author=Cornelius O'Boyle|title=The Art of Medicine: Medical Teaching at the University of Paris, 1250-1400|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ERqL6h_uAbQC&pg=PA200|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1998|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-11124-0|page=200}}</ref> Some of the medical works that were attributed to him are considered to be by [[Bartholomew of Salerno]] instead.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Ernest Wickersheimer|author2=Danielle Jacquart|title=Dictionnaire biographique des médecins en France au Moyen âge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L49VVsggJY4C&pg=PA38|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1979|publisher=Librairie Droz|isbn=978-2-600-03384-8|page=38|language=fr}}</ref> In 1348, at the time of the [[Black Death]], he wrote on the [[bubonic plague|plague]].<ref name="GlickLivesey2005"/>
