'''Julije Makanec''' (19 September 1904 – 7 June 1945{{sfn|Karaula|Miškulin|2014|p=81}}) was an ethnic [[Croats|Croatian]] politician, teacher, philosopher and writer. During World War II, he was the Minister of Education of the [[Independent State of Croatia]] and a high-ranking member of the [[Ustaše]].{{sfn|Macut|2013|p=147}} [[File:Prof. Julije pl. Makanec.jpg|thumb|Minister of Education in the Independent State of Croatia (NDH)]]

Makanec was born in [[Sarajevo]].{{sfn|Karaula|Miškulin|2014|p=81}} He was educated in [[Osijek]] and [[Bihać]], and studied philosophy at the [[University of Zagreb]], where he obtained a Ph.D. in 1927.{{sfn|Karaula|Miškulin|2014|p=81}} Between 1929 and 1940 he served as a gymnasium professor in [[Koprivnica]], [[Bjelovar]] and several other places in Croatia, as well as in [[Leskovac]], [[Serbia]].{{sfn|Karaula|Miškulin|2014|p=81}}  In November 1940, as a member of the [[Croatian Peasant Party]], he became the mayor of [[Bjelovar]].{{sfn|Macut|2013|p=149}} Here he played an important role in the [[Bjelovar rebellion]] of 8 April that year when, after the revolt by Croats in the [[Royal Yugoslav Army]] during the early days of [[invasion of Yugoslavia]], he declared the "resurrection of the Croatian state".{{sfn|Karaula|Miškulin|2014|p=81}}{{sfn|Macut|2013|p=148}}{{sfn|Yeomans|2013|p=92}} 

By his own account, Makanec swore the [[Ustaše]] oath in April 1941, days after the establishment of the [[Independent State of Croatia]], but historians believe Makanec may have joined the Ustaše much earlier, in late 1939 or early 1940.{{sfn|Macut|2013|p=149}}{{sfn|Karaula|Miškulin|2014|p=82}} Shortly after the formation of the Ustaše government he served as [[adjutant]] in the Croatian army's Bilogora headquarters, in Bjelovar.{{sfn|Macut|2013|p=152}} From 1942 he was the chief of spiritual upbringing in the Ustaša Youth. In March 1943 he was named extraordinary professor of philosophy at the [[Faculty of Philosophy in Zagreb]].{{sfn|Karaula|Miškulin|2014|p=81}} In October 1943 he became the Independent State of Croatia's Minister of National Education.{{sfn|Karaula|Miškulin|2014|p=81}} He also wrote books in his field as well as contributing to various periodicals and newspapers.{{cn|date=January 2016}}

In a 1942 brochure titled ''Ustaše Virtues'' (''Ustaške vrline''), Makanec wrote: "[...] every community has the right to exterminate, destroy, or at least render harmless those individuals who weaken it and bring it to ruin due to their utter lack of virtue."{{sfn|Jakovina|2016}}{{sfn|Macut|2013|p=156}}{{sfn|Milekic|2016}}

On 6 April 1945, shortly before [[Yugoslav Partisans]] entered Zagreb, Makanec fled the city in a group of sixteen government ministers. On 17 May, they surrendered to the British in [[Tamsweg]], Austria, and were extradited to Yugoslav authorities. After a one-day trial before a military tribunal in Zagreb on 6 June he was sentenced to death for high treason and war crimes and executed by firing squad in the morning of the following day.{{sfn|Macut|2013|p=147}}{{sfn|Karaula|Miškulin|2014|p=80}}

